  "articleBody": "&lt;p&gt;&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/loose.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Herb-Banner.png?itok=LIkWUoaF&quot;

          alt=&quot;Ultimate Guide to Fresh Herbs&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Herbs can magically flavor up dishes without resorting to loads of &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/21-lower-sodium-solutions/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;salt&lt;/a&gt;, butter, and cheese. Adding a little green to a meal not only makes it prettier and tastier, but can pack some awesome &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.huffingtonpost.com/leo-galland-md/healthy-herbs_b_853597.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;health benefits&lt;/a&gt;, too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And while those 5-year-old dried and bottled versions are convenient, it&amp;rsquo;s worth it to splurge on the fresh stuff every once in a while (or &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bhg.com/gardening/vegetable/herbs/herb-care-guide/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;grow your own&lt;/a&gt; at home)! While adding herbs &amp;mdash; dried or fresh &amp;mdash; to any dish can add healthy vitamins and &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nutritionj.com/content/9/1/3&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;antioxidants&lt;/a&gt;, they may lose nutritional value during the &lt;a href=&quot;http://nutritionovereasy.com/2011/04/do-dried-herbs-and-spices-have-nutritional-value/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;drying process&lt;/a&gt;, so stick with fresh if available &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22256774&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ideas and methods of fresh herb basic research based on constituent structure theory.&lt;/a&gt; Jia, X., Zheng, Z., Huang, Y., et al. School of Pharmacy, Jiangsu University, Zhenjiang, China. Zhongguo Zhong Yao Za Zhi, 2011 Sep;36(18):2595-8.&lt;/cite&gt;. Read on to find out how to use some of the most popular herbs in their fresh state, and how to store them for later use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;The How-tos&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1. Store fresh.&lt;/strong&gt; Rinse herbs with cool water to remove dirt, gently shake off excess moisture, and pat dry with paper towels or a clean dishcloth. Find a medium-sized &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.simplyrecipes.com/recipes/how_to_store_parsley_cilantro_and_other_fresh_herbs/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;jar&lt;/a&gt; and fill with a few inches of water. Trim the ends of the herb stems so that the bunch fits with the leaves above the jar&amp;rsquo;s edge. Leave them on the counter, or store in the refrigerator, covered loosely with a plastic bag.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2. Deep freeze.&lt;/strong&gt; Chop up fresh herbs and pop them into an ice cube tray to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.organicgardening.com/cook/how-freeze-herbs&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;freeze&lt;/a&gt; for later use. Try freezing them&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.thekitchn.com/freeze-herbs-in-olive-oil-173648&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt; in olive oil&lt;/a&gt; for use in saut&amp;eacute;s or roasted dishes!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3. Mincing made easy.&lt;/strong&gt; A microplane &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/holiday-gift-guide-health/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;mill&lt;/a&gt; allows users to mince herbs quickly without bruising them or making a big mess. Not a fan of kitchen gadgets? Get yourself a sharp knife, and dry those fresh herbs very well. For best chopability, make sure to pat herbs dry with a clean dishtowel or paper towels before they hit the blade.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4. Grow your own.&lt;/strong&gt; Try &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/22-cheap-and-easy-ways-to-eat-healthy-041012/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;growing your own herbs&lt;/a&gt; in an &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/holiday-gift-guide-health/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;indoor herb garden&lt;/a&gt; or use a few small planters and an empty &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.epicurious.com/articlesguides/seasonalcooking/farmtotable/herbgarden&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;windowsill&lt;/a&gt;. Then you&amp;rsquo;ll have a fresh, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.aarp.org/health/alternative-medicine/info-06-2010/grow-herbs-feel-better.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;healthy&lt;/a&gt; way to give flavor to dishes right at your fingertips.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5. Air dry.&lt;/strong&gt; While we often prefer fresh herbs, sometimes they can quickly &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.thekitchn.com/quick-tip-when-to-use-dried-he-133710&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;rack up a grocery bill&lt;/a&gt;. Try buying in bulk, and drying them yourself for later use. Secure stems with twine or a rubber band and &lt;a href=&quot;http://nchfp.uga.edu/how/dry/herbs.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;hang them&lt;/a&gt; upside down in a warm, dry place that&amp;rsquo;s away from direct sunlight. Pop a paper bag over the herbs to prevent them from getting dusty.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s Talk Herbs&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thyme to get herby fully loaded! If you don&amp;rsquo;t hate us too much after the herb puns, then read on for descriptions of some of the most common herbs, what they taste like, and how to use them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Basil&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Basil_604.jpg?itok=FSy9GINb&quot;

          alt=&quot;Basil&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Basil comes in green and purple varieties, but the green one is probably what we&amp;rsquo;re most used to. Add the fresh leaves at the end of cooking for max flavor (and to preserve greenness &amp;mdash; they turn brown if exposed to heat for too long!). Added Bonus: Basil is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties from its oil eugenol, which can block enzymes in the body that cause swelling &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21939359&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Eugenol enhances the chemotherapeutic potential of gemcitabine and induces anticarcinogenic and anti-inflammatory activity in human cervical cancer cells.&lt;/a&gt; Hussain, A., Brahmbhatt, K., Priyani, A., et al., Department of Biotechnology, Manipal University, Dubai, United Arab Emirates. Cancer Biotherapy Radiopharmaceuticals, 2011 Oct;26(5):519-27.&lt;/cite&gt;. Since the leaves are easily bruised, try using fresh basil whole or tearing it gently with your hands.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Minty and slightly peppery, with a touch of sweetness&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect for: &lt;/strong&gt;Sauces, sandwiches, homemade &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/make-healthier-pizza/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;pizza&lt;/a&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Two cups of fresh basil leaves make this &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-pesto-cheese-pizza/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Fresh Pesto and Cheese Pizza&lt;/a&gt; something special. For dessert, try this &lt;a href=&quot;http://katieatthekitchendoor.com/2011/06/28/lemon-basil-sorbet/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;lemon-basil sorbet&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Bay Leaves&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Bay-Leaves_604.jpg?itok=2jxAIwXh&quot;

          alt=&quot;Bay Leaves&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;There are two types of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.seriouseats.com/2011/12/spice-hunting-bay-leaf-turkish-californian-how-to-use.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;bay leaf&lt;/a&gt; &amp;mdash; Mediterranean and Californian. The Mediterranean is milder in flavor. Bay leaves are usually used &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.tablefare.com/spicelibrary/index.php?spiceID=13&amp;amp;n=Bay-Leaf&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;dry&lt;/a&gt; to reduce some of their bitterness. Commonly used in classic chicken soup, some compounds in bay leaves may help relieve upset stomachs &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22082096&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Antidiarrheal activity of Laurus nobilis L. leaf extract in rats.&lt;/a&gt; Qnais, E.Y., Abdulla, F.A., Kaddumi, E.G. et al. Department of Biology and Biotechnology, Faculty of Science, Hashemite University, Zarka, Jordan. Journal of Medicinal Food, 2012 Jan;15(1):51-7.&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Woody, sweet, citrusy, nutty&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Soups, stews, and saut&amp;eacute;ed dishes.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick:&lt;/strong&gt; Pop a leaf into this colorful &lt;a href=&quot;http://katieatthekitchendoor.com/2011/12/08/beet-and-chickpea-salad/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;beet and chickpea salad&lt;/a&gt;, but don&amp;rsquo;t forget to remove it before serving!&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;em&gt;Photo: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/evaekeblad/445040259/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Eva the Weaver&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Chives&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Chives_604_0.jpg?itok=NeVt2MLm&quot;

          alt=&quot;Chives&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;This herb, which looks a lot like the grass in your front lawn, is filled with antioxidants, vitamins A and C, and &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/complementaryandalternativemedicine/herbsvitaminsandminerals/phytochemicals&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;phytochemicals&lt;/a&gt; (which have antioxidant-like benefits) &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21438046&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Comparative study on Allium schoenoprasum cultivated plant and Allium schoenoprasum tissue culture organs antioxidant status.&lt;/a&gt; Stajner, D., Popovic, B.M., Calic-Dragosavac, D. et al. Faculty of Agriculture, University of Novi Sad, Novi Sad, Yugoslavia. Phytotherapy Research, 2011 Nov;25(11):1618-22.&lt;/cite&gt; &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15305309&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Allium schoenoprasum L., as a natural antioxidant.&lt;/a&gt; Stajner, D., Canadanovic-Brunet, J., Pavlovic, A., et al. Faculty of Agriculture, University of Novi Sad, Trg Dositeja Obradovica, Novi Sad, Yuoslavia. Phytotherapy Research, 2004 Jul;18(7):522-4.&lt;/cite&gt;. Easy chive-chopping tip: Try &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.williams-sonoma.com/recipe/tip/snipping-chives.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;snipping&lt;/a&gt; with a sharp set of kitchen shears.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Light oniony flavor&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Cutting down the heaviness of rich foods like cream sauces and risotto.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Chop n&amp;rsquo; top a healthier loaded potato with a dollop of plain Greek yogurt (our favorite sour cream stand-in), or use to season &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-healthy-potato-wedge-alternative/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;baked &amp;ldquo;fake potato&amp;rdquo; wedges&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;em&gt;Photo: &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/grongar/4830422541/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;grongar&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Cilantro&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Cilantro_604.jpg?itok=NMmZfzQt&quot;

          alt=&quot;Cilantro&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Cilantro has got a distinct flavor that you&amp;rsquo;ll either love or &lt;a href=&quot;http://ihatecilantro.com/taste.php&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;despise&lt;/a&gt;. The green herb that&amp;rsquo;s sometimes confused with parsley has high concentrations of carotenoids, which are a good source of &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/vitamins-minerals-guide/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;vitamin A&lt;/a&gt; &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22812633&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Assessment of vitamin and carotenoid concentrations of emerging food products: edible microgreens.&lt;/a&gt; Xiao, Z. Lester, G.E., Luo, Y., et al. Department of Nutrition and Food Science, University of Maryland. Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry, 2012 Aug 8;60(31):7644-51.&lt;/cite&gt;. Cilantro is multifaceted &amp;mdash; its dried seeds are called &lt;a href=&quot;http://whatscookingamerica.net/cilantro.htm&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;coriander&lt;/a&gt;, which is often used for pickling and in curries.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Bright, and citrusy. Some say it can taste a little &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/20/cilantro-aversion-gene-study_n_1901124.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;soapy&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Salsa, chutneys, guacamole, and Mexican dishes.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Add to peachy &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-pan-seared-fish-tacos/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;pan-seared fish tacos&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Dill&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/DIll_604.jpg?itok=KZEvlU7n&quot;

          alt=&quot;Dill&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Known as the classic flavoring for pickles (and as Tommy&amp;rsquo;s younger brother on&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nick.com/shows/rugrats/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt; Rugrats&lt;/a&gt;), dill is a wispy little herb traditionally used to &lt;a href=&quot;http://books.google.com/books?hl=en&amp;amp;lr=&amp;amp;id=KXrlJohBTF0C&amp;amp;oi=fnd&amp;amp;pg=PA1&amp;amp;dq=dill+weed+for+insomnia&amp;amp;ots=__8FKF67eX&amp;amp;sig=BxhsBy4wQuJe63zP4lnZs52aiDs#v=onepage&amp;amp;q&amp;amp;f=false&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;treat insomnia&lt;/a&gt;. Dill may also help protect against age-related cognitive impairment &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23028394&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Evaluation of Safety and Protective Effect of Combined Extract of Cissampelos pareira and Anethum graveolens (PM52) against Age-Related Cognitive Impairment.&lt;/a&gt; Thukham-Mee, W., Wattanathorn, J. Neurosxience Program Department of Physiology and Graduate School, Faculty of Medicine, Khon Kaen University, Khon Kaen, Thailand. Evidence-Based Complementary and Alternative Medicine, 2012;2012:674101.&lt;/cite&gt;. It&amp;rsquo;s also a staple to flavor classic &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/page/2/?s=herb&amp;amp;searchsubmit=Search&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;chicken noodle soup&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Sweet, grassy&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Pickling, fish dishes, and dressings&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Combine dill with avocado and Greek yogurt as a &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-baked-salmon-avocado-dill-yogurt/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;light tangy topping&lt;/a&gt; for fish, or transform boring eggs in these &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.glowkitchen.com/2011/02/dill-red-pepper-scrambled-eggs/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;dill and red pepper scramble&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;em&gt;Photo:&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/bagaball/5777241197/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;bagaball&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Lemongrass&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Lemongrass_604.jpg?itok=pykS1anS&quot;

          alt=&quot;Lemongrass&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Essential in Thai cooking, studies suggest that lemongrass can have anti-inflammatory powers that reduce swelling and help with fluid balance in the body (at least in rats) &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23065287&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Phytochemical composition of Cymbopogon citratus and Eucalyptus citriodora essential oils and their anti-inflammatory and analgesic properties on Wistar rats.&lt;/a&gt; Gbenou, J.D., Ahounou, J.F. Akakpo, H.B., et al. Laboratoire de Pharmaconosie et des Huiles Essentielles, Facute des Sciences de la Sante, Faculte des Sciences et Techniques, Universite d&amp;rsquo;Abomey Calavi, Cotonou, Benin. Molecular biology reports, 2012 Oct. 14&lt;/cite&gt;. Lemongrass is used to season dishes from pad thai to curry. When cooking with the stalks, make sure to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.thefoodinmybeard.com/basics/how-to-use-lemongrass.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;remove and discard off the bulb&lt;/a&gt; (the rounded white part at the bottom) and remove the tough, outer leaves.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;zesty, slightly spicy, lemon flavor&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Curry, Asian soups, scented rice, marinades&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Use three stalks of fresh lemongrass in this &lt;a href=&quot;http://katieatthekitchendoor.com/2010/05/03/lemongrass-edamame-and-winning/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;ginger chicken&lt;/a&gt; dish.&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;em&gt;Photo: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/papayatreelimited/3101342419/%20&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;papayatreelimited&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Marjoram&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Marjoram_604.jpg?itok=zJs8KC9m&quot;

          alt=&quot;Marjoram&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;This herb is often mistaken for its close cousin oregano because of their similarly shaped oval leaves. The major difference? Marjoram is a tad sweeter. The herb is also said to help  &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.webmd.com/vitamins-supplements/ingredientmono-563-MARJORAM.aspx?activeIngredientId=563&amp;amp;activeIngredientName=MARJORAM&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;alleviate&lt;/a&gt; stomach pain, insomnia, and a lack of appetite.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Grassy, lemony, slightly sweet&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Flavoring meats and poultry, as well as stuffing.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;We like to use marjoram in this &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-cauliflower-crust-pizza/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;cauliflower crust pizza&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;em&gt;Photo:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/rainbreaw/4123489950/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;rainbreaw&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Mint&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Mint_604.jpg?itok=wYUhUBeT&quot;

          alt=&quot;Mint&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Mint comes in many varieties, but the two most common are peppermint and spearmint. Spearmint is lighter, sweeter, and more palatable, while peppermint has a stronger bite from the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/002673.htm&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;menthol&lt;/a&gt; in its leaves. These bright green little leaves can aid &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/drink-for-every-situation/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;digestion&lt;/a&gt;, and mint tea has been known to soothe &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/best-foods-hangover/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;hangovers&lt;/a&gt; &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;Herbal remedies for dyspepsia: peppermint seems effective. Prescrire International. 2008 Jun;17(95):121-3.&lt;/cite&gt; &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;Herbal remedies for dyspepsia: peppermint seems effective. Prescrire International. 2008 Jun; 17(95):121-3.&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Refreshing, cool&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/60-healthier-drinks-for-boozing-030712/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;Mojitos&lt;/a&gt;, paired with lamb, or combined with chocolate (peppermint patty, anyone?)!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Try it in this lentil&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-lentil-feta-tabbouleh-021712/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;tabbouleh&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Oregano&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Oregano_604.jpg?itok=EblGCzNQ&quot;

          alt=&quot;Oregano&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;This herb usually falls into two categories: Mexican and Mediterranean. They're similar, but Mexican oregano may taste more citrusy than the sweet, peppery Mediterranean variety. Oregano is a&lt;a href=&quot;http://nutritiondata.self.com/foods-000140000000000000000.html&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt; source&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.umm.edu/altmed/articles/omega-3-000316.htm&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;omega-3 fatty acids&lt;/a&gt;, which are essential for heart health. Oregano may also help combat some types of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.foxnews.com/health/2012/04/24/oregano-shown-to-effectively-destroy-prostate-cancer-cells/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;cancer cells&lt;/a&gt; (though what we add to dinner will likely have a minimal effect) &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21535822&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Oregano: chemical analysis and evaluation of its antimalarial, antioxidant, and cytotoxic activities.&lt;/a&gt; El Babili, F., Bouajila, J., Souchard, J.P., et al., Faculte des Sciences Pharmaceutiques de Toulouse, Laboratoire de Botanique-Mycologie, Toulouse, France. Journal of Food Science, 2011 Apr;76(3):C512-8.&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Lemony, minty, peppery (depending on type)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Seasoning &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/make-healthier-pizza/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;pizza&lt;/a&gt; crusts and pasta dishes, as well as &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/healthy-recipe-substitutions/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;homemade dressings&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/cook-thanksgiving-turkey-recipe-111312/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;poultry rubs&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Add fresh oregano to this five-ingredient&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-veggie-packed-quinoa/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;veggie-packed quinoa&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Parsley&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Parsley_604.jpg?itok=cmeFigAh&quot;

          alt=&quot;Parsley&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This powerful little green gets some brain-boosting clout from quercetin, a chemical found in the herb that helps protect brain cells from free radical damage &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;Polychlorinated Biphenyls-Induced Oxidative Stress on Rat Hippocampus: A Neuroprotective Role of Quercetin. Selvakumar, K., Bavithra, S., Krishnamoorthy, G., et al. Department of Endocrinology, Dr. ALM Post Graduate Institute of Basic Medical Sciences, University of Madras, Chennai 600113, India. Scientific World Journal, 2012.&lt;/cite&gt;. Added bonus: Parsley&amp;rsquo;s polyphenols and carotenoids may help &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/foods-that-protect-from-the-sun/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;protect skin&lt;/a&gt; from sun damage. Find it in curly or flat-leafed varieties.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Grassy, mild, slightly peppery (flat-leaf only)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Pasta dishes, eggs, fish and meat&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Top &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-mexican-sweet-potatoes/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Mexican-style sweet potatoes&lt;/a&gt; with some fresh parsley, or use a bunch on top of this &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-fig-onion-flatbread-pizza/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;fig and onion flatbread pizza&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Rosemary&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Rosemary_604.jpg?itok=5Bnq7KC6&quot;

          alt=&quot;Rosemary&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;This needle-y herb is often used in mashed potatoes or &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.food.com/recipe/rosemary-infused-oil-113013&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;infused in oil&lt;/a&gt;. When using it at home, make sure to strip the needles from the woody stems before chopping and adding to recipes. Rosemary is rich in &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.brainpower.org/research/carnosic-acid.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;carnosic acid&lt;/a&gt;, an antioxidant that may help limit weight gain and improve cholesterol levels &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21676274&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Carnosic acid-rich rosemary (Rosmarinus officinalis L.) leaf extract limits weight gain and improves cholesterol levels and glycaemia in mice on a high-fat diet.&lt;/a&gt; Ibarra, A., Cases, J., Roller, M. et al. Naturex, Inc. South Hackensack, NJ. The British Journal of Nutrition, 2011 Oct;106(8):1182-9.&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Like pine, faintly lemony&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Potatoes or poultry dishes&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Picks: &lt;/strong&gt;Add a punch of flavor to &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/quinoa-stuffed-mushrooms-healthy-recipe/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;quinoa and veggie stuffed mushrooms&lt;/a&gt; or an adult beverage like &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/60-healthier-drinks-for-boozing-030712/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;rosemary-cucumber lemonade&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Sage&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Sage_0.jpg?itok=5CLej8BZ&quot;

          alt=&quot;Sage&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Behind it&amp;rsquo;s soft, fuzzy leaves, sage hides hordes of &lt;a href=&quot;http://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/jf00039a012&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;antioxidants,&lt;/a&gt; including flavonoids and phenolic acids, which can help lower risk for cardiovascular disease &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23240623&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Antibacterial, allelopathic and antioxidant activities of essential oil of Salvia officinalis L. growing wild in the Atlas Mountains of Morocco.&lt;/a&gt; Bouajaj, S., Benyamna, A., Bouamama, H. et al. a Laboratoire de Chimie Organique Appliquee, Faculte des Sciences Semlalia, Universite Cadi Ayyad, Prince Moulay Abdallah, Marrakech, Morroco. Natural Product Research, 2012 Dec 14.&lt;/cite&gt; &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2666177/&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Phenolic acids suppress adipocyte lipolysis via activation of the nicotinic acid receptor GPR109A (HM74a/PUMA-G)&lt;/a&gt;. Ren, N., Kaplan, R., Hernandez, M. et al. Department of Cardiovascular Diseases, Merck Research Laboratories, Rahway, NJ. Journal of Lipid Research, 2009 May; 50(5): 908-914.&lt;/cite&gt;. Sage is also on our list of &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/foods-pain-relief/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;foods that fight pain&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste:&lt;/strong&gt; slightly peppery, faintly minty&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;Brussels sprouts, anything using brown butter, &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/healthy-thanksgiving-recipes-111512/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;roasted squash&lt;/a&gt;, rich or creamy dishes, sausage&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Use these in &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-vegetable-goat-cheese-quesadilla/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;goat cheese quesadillas&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Tarragon&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Tarragon_604.jpg?itok=a4Y_s65H&quot;

          alt=&quot;Tarragon&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;Often paired with chicken or eggs, this long-leafed herb has a distinct licorice-like flavor. The ancient Greeks chewed on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.herbwisdom.com/herb-tarragon.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;tarragon&lt;/a&gt; to treat toothaches. It&amp;rsquo;s also been touted as a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Artemisia+dracunculus&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;digestive aid &lt;/a&gt;and may help those with diabetes by reducing blood sugar &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21942448&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Artemisia dracunculus L. (tarragon): a critical review of its traditional use, chemical composition, pharmacology, and safety.&lt;/a&gt; Obolskiy, D., Pischel, I., Feistel, B., et al. Center for Pharmacognosy and Phytotherapy, The School of Pharmacy (Univeristy of London), United Kingdom. Journal of Agricultural Food and Chemistry, 2011 Nov. 9;59(21):11367-84.&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;like licorice or fennel, sweet&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For: &lt;/strong&gt;French cooking, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.eatingwell.com/healthy_cooking/quick_healthy_cooking/quick_healthy_bearnaise_sauce&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;b&amp;eacute;arnaise sauce&lt;/a&gt;, chicken, fish, and egg dishes&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Use tarragon to whip up homemade &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/healthier-dressings-condiments-marinades/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;green goddess dressing&lt;/a&gt;, or in this &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-tomato-peach-gazpacho/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;tomato and peach gazpacho&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
(&lt;em&gt;Photo: &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.flickr.com/photos/magnetha/4380426505/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Kathleen Farley&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h5&gt;Thyme&lt;/h5&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
  class=&quot;media media-element-container media-g_full_width_inline_image&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;img
    src=&quot;http://greatist.com/sites/default/files/styles/article_main/public/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Thyme_604.jpg?itok=5CE11KCh&quot;

          alt=&quot;Thyme&quot;
    
        class=&quot;media-element file-g-full-width-inline-image&quot;
  /&gt;

  
  &lt;/span&gt;This tiny-leaved herb&amp;rsquo;s most often used in French cooking. Make sure to strip the leaves from the woody stems before adding them to recipes (unless it&amp;rsquo;s used to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.chow.com/recipes/10566-bouquet-garni&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;flavor a roast&lt;/a&gt; or soup and then removed before serving!). Run the back of a knife along the stems (the opposite direction of growth) to easily remove the leaves. Added bonus: Thyme is known for its antioxidant content &lt;cite data-cite-reference class=&quot;citation-reference&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22744949&quot; rel=&quot;&quot;&gt;Antioxidative effect of thyme (Thymus vulgaris) in sunflower oil.&lt;/a&gt; Zaborowska, Z., Przygonski, K., Bilska, A. Institute of Agricultural and Food Biotechnology in Warsaw, Department of Food Concentrates and Startch Products in Poznan, Starolecka, Poznan, Poland. Acta Scientiarum Polonorum, 2012 Jul-Sep;11(3):283-91.&lt;/cite&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Taste: &lt;/strong&gt;Lemony, slightly peppery and minty&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Perfect For:&lt;/strong&gt; Stews, rice dishes, dips, and sauces&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Greatist Recipe Pick: &lt;/strong&gt;Use a few sprigs in these &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-mashed-potato-alternative/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;healthier mashed &amp;ldquo;potatoes&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a&gt; or as a major player in this &lt;a href=&quot;http://greatist.com/health/recipe-cranberryorange-sauce-thyme/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;cranberry-orange sauce&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
